<font color="#FF0000">RESPONSE TO ED RAMON</font><br>
<tt>Sun Jul 27  9:12:02 US/Eastern 1997
</tt><p>
Ed,<br><br>
So as not to lose the continuity, I am going to respond to you in this thread.<br><br>
I accept your apology with the understanding that not many people, who claim to see only in &quot;black and white&quot;, offer apologies. Thanks. Your correspondence shows the importance of this site.<br><br>
When you speak of &quot;rejection&quot; I see two different things. One is a rejection of our ideas or opinions, the other is simply being ignored. I maintain that the latter is the worse form of rejection. I experienced this many times when I returned from Vietnam. <br><br>
I didn't seek solace from the hippies. But I did expect some form of comfort from those who said that it was a good idea that I go to Vietnam. Many times, when the subject of Vietnam came up, an uncomfortable silence followed. I have an article on my website by a guy named Roland Kunkel - a PTSD vet like yourself. He has much to say about the VFW and the VA.<br><br>
People need to be reminded of the horror of war. War has very lasting effects. Our people lost sight of the &quot;blood, feces and urine&quot; in the Gulf War. <br><br>
I, too, want vets to hold up their heads. But we must realize that it is not necessary to steamroll someone else in order to be proud of our accomplishments. Divergent views must be respected. The truth is: none of us are 100% correct.<br><br>

<p><code>-- wingman@greene.xtn.net  (Tom Dier) </code><p>


